Package ohos.aafwk.ability

Class LifecycleObserver

  • java.lang.Object
    • ohos.aafwk.ability.LifecycleObserver
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ILifecycleObserver

    public class LifecycleObserver
extends Object
implements ILifecycleObserver
    Observes and responds to lifecycle changes.

    Lifecycle dispatches a lifecycle event to a registered LifecycleObserver. LifecycleObserver then implements lifecycle callbacks for Ability or AbilitySlice. This allows your application to have a decoupled architecture where Ability or AbilitySlice takes only a single responsibility.

    You should inherit the LifecycleObserver class, override lifecycle callback methods as required, and call Lifecycle#addObserver(ILifecycleObserver) to register a LifecycleObserver with Lifecycle. The callback methods in LifecycleObserver provide the same functions as those provided in Ability and AbilitySlice, but they are called in different sequence. The system calls those in Ability and AbilitySlice first and then those in LifecycleObserver. You are advised to use LifecycleObserver for lifecycle callbacks of Ability and AbilitySlice when your application is complicated.

    Since:
    1
    See Also:
    Lifecycle, ILifecycleObserver, LifecycleStateObserver

    • Method Detail

      • onStart

        public void onStart​(Intent intent)
        Called back in response to an ON_START event, where the startup information is carried in the intent parameter.

        This method initializes an Ability or AbilitySlice and is called back only once during the entire lifecycle. You are advised to implement some initialization logic using this method, for example, you can initialize a timer or define some global objects.

        Parameters:
        intent - Indicates the startup information.
        See Also:
        Ability.onStart(Intent), AbilitySlice.onStart(Intent)

      • onInactive

        public void onInactive​()
        Called back in response to an ON_INACTIVE event.

        When an ON_INACTIVE event is received, the ability or ability slice is in the INACTIVE state. INACTIVE is an intermediate state before the state changes to ACTIVE or BACKGROUND. In this state, the UI may be visible but is not interactive. You are advised not to use this method to invoke complex service logic.

        See Also:
        Ability.onInactive(), AbilitySlice.onInactive()

      • onActive

        public void onActive​()
        Called back in response to an ON_ACTIVE event.

        When an ON_ACTIVE event is received, the ability or ability slice is in the foreground and is interactive.

        See Also:
        Ability.onActive(), AbilitySlice.onActive()

      • onBackground

        public void onBackground​()
        Called back in response to an ON_BACKGROUND event.

        When an ON_BACKGROUND event is received, the ability or ability slice is invisible. You are advised to suspend the threads related to this ability or ability slice and clear resources for more system memory.

        See Also:
        Ability.onBackground(), AbilitySlice.onBackground()

      • onForeground

        public void onForeground​(Intent intent)
        Called back in response to an ON_FOREGROUND event, where information for the ability or ability slice to go back to the ACTIVE state is carried in the intent parameter.

        When an ON_FOREGROUND event is received, the ability or ability slice returns to the foreground. You can use this method to implement re-initialization or adjust the UI display by using the intent parameter.

        Parameters:
        intent - Indicates the information for the ability or ability slice to go back to the ACTIVE state.
        See Also:
        Ability.onForeground(Intent), AbilitySlice.onForeground(Intent)

      • onStop

        public void onStop​()
        Called back in response to an ON_STOP event.

        This method is called back when the lifecycle of the ability or ability slice is destroyed. You can reclaim resources using this method.

        See Also:
        Ability.onStop(), AbilitySlice.onStop()
